"Yvon-Durocher G., Jones J.I., Trimmer M., Woodward G., Montoya J.M.","Warming alters the metabolic balance of ecosystems",2010,"Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences","365","1549",,"2117","2126",,,10.1098/rstb.2010.0038,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77954725216&partnerID=40&md5=f4fc094bfd02cec4f3992046ccd64cd5","School of Biological and Chemical Sciences, Queen Mary University of London, London E1 4NS, United Kingdom; Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, MacLean Building, Benson Lane, Crowmarsh Gifford, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Institute of Marine Sciences (ICM-CSIC), Pg. Maritim de la Barceloneta, 37-49, 8003 Barcelona, Spain","Yvon-Durocher, G., School of Biological and Chemical Sciences, Queen Mary University of London, London E1 4NS, United Kingdom; Jones, J.I., Centre for Ecology and Hydrology, MacLean Building, Benson Lane, Crowmarsh Gifford, Wallingford OX10 8BB, United Kingdom; Trimmer, M., School of Biological and Chemical Sciences, Queen Mary University of London, London E1 4NS, United Kingdom; Woodward, G., School of Biological and Chemical Sciences, Queen Mary University of London, London E1 4NS, United Kingdom; Montoya, J.M., School of Biological and Chemical Sciences, Queen Mary University of London, London E1 4NS, United Kingdom, Institute of Marine Sciences (ICM-CSIC), Pg. Maritim de la Barceloneta, 37-49, 8003 Barcelona, Spain","The carbon cycle modulates climate change, via the regulation of atmospheric CO2, and it represents one of the most important services provided by ecosystems. However, considerable uncertainties remain concerning potential feedback between the biota and the climate. In particular, it is unclear how global warming will affect the metabolic balance between the photosynthetic fixation and respiratory release of CO2 at the ecosystem scale. Here, we present a combination of experimental field data from freshwater mesocosms, and theoretical predictions derived from the metabolic theory of ecology to investigate whether warming will alter the capacity of ecosystems to absorb CO2. Our manipulative experiment simulated the temperature increases predicted for the end of the century and revealed that ecosystem respiration increased at a faster rate than primary production, reducing carbon sequestration by 13 per cent. These results confirmed our theoretical predictions based on the differential activation energies of these two processes. Using only the activation energies for whole ecosystem photosynthesis and respiration we provide a theoretical prediction that accurately quantified the precise magnitude of the reduction in carbon sequestration observed experimentally. We suggest the combination of whole-ecosystem manipulative experiments and ecological theory is one of the most promising and fruitful research areas to predict the impacts of climate change on key ecosystem services. © 2010 The Royal Society.","Carbon cycle; Carbon sequestration; Ecosystem respiration; Global warming; Gross primary production; Metabolic theory","carbon; fresh water; carbon; carbon cycle; freshwater ecosystem; global warming; mesocosm; metabolism; primary production; respiration; article; ecosystem; greenhouse effect; metabolism; photosynthesis; temperature; theoretical model; thermodynamics; metabolism; Carbon; Ecosystem; Fresh Water; Global Warming; Models, Theoretical; Photosynthesis; Temperature; Thermodynamics; Carbon; Ecosystem; Fresh Water; Global Warming; Models, Theoretical; Photosynthesis; Temperature; Thermodynamics",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Carbon",,,,"Allen, A.P., Gillooly, J.F., Brown, J.H., Linking the global carbon cycle to individual metabolism (2005) Funct. Ecol., 19, pp. 202-213. , doi:10.1111/j.1365-2435.2005.00952.x; Arnone, J.A., Prolonged suppression of ecosystem carbon dioxide uptake after an anomalously warm year (2008) Nature, 455, pp. 383-386. , doi:10.1038/nature07296; Atkin, O.K., Tjoelker, M.G., Thermal a